<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: 21 Nov 2007
Source: CostaRicaHoliday [edited]
<http://www.costaricaholiday.co.uk/blog/?p=290>


'Ojo de Gallo' affecting coffee plantations in Costa Rica
----------------------------------------------------------
Coffee plantations that are located more than 1400 meters [4593 feet]
above sea level are being affected by a fungus known as 'ojo de
gallo,' which has prompted the Institute of Farming Research and
Extension to request that all coffee growers spray their crops that
exceed this altitude limit.

The spray to be used is a non-systemic compound with a fungicide
action that is most effective when used against soil based diseases.
It is already used to control another disease known as rhizoctonia
that can be found in rice, potatoes, vegetables as well as being
found in vegetable seeds, cotton, sugar canes and beets and various
other plants.

Along with the use of the spray, farmers are recommended to start
unshading their plants, clean out the weeds and prune the plants.

Ojo de gallo affects the leaves of the coffee plants forcing both the
leaves and the berries or beans to fall off of the plants and if not
checked, has the potential to destroy a large amount of crops.

[Byline: carolinew]

